[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is the whole repo. One file, 1,700 bytes, shorter than the average React component, and it makes Claude, Cursor, and Codex write up to 90% less code. No model, no framework, just a prompt that'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tells your agent to be lazy. So, what is it? Ponytail is a skill, a prompt you drop into your coding agent. The pitch. Make it think like the laziest senior dev in the room.'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You know the type. Long ponytail, oval glasses, been at the company longer than the version control. You show him 50 lines, he says nothing, and replaces them with one. 15,000 stars in, a lot of you'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'apparently want that guy living inside your editor. There\'s a catch to it, but you have to watch it work first. Watch it actually work. Ask a normal agent for a feature flag system, and it builds the whole thing. A'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'database table, rollout percentages, a cache, an admin API. The lazy one? About 20 lines on the Redis you already run, plus a comment marking exactly where it breaks. And'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s not just feature flags. Ask for a sort? It skips writing a quick sort by hand and calls the one your runtime already ships. 24 lines gone. Ask it to validate an email?'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'One line, because regex can\'t really validate an email anyway. Only a delivery attempt can. Ask for a caching layer? First, it asks whether you\'ve actually measured the problem. Usually, you haven\'t. So, it writes less code. You'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'already believe that. Here\'s the part you might not. It\'s also cheaper, and it\'s faster. According to the repo\'s own benchmark, 10 runs per task, median reported, the lazy agent ran three to'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'six times faster and cost up to 3/4 less. The less code part? 80 to 94% less. The nastiest example, one baseline run ballooned a simple countdown timer into'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a dashboard. 190 lines. Pony Tail did the same task in 13. Now, your instinct is right to flinch. Less code usually means flimsier code. So, does it? The'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'benchmark runs every answer through a correctness gate. If the code doesn\'t work, that arm fails. Lazy is not allowed to mean broken. The honest catch, only three of the five tasks'

[02:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually execute. The other two get checked for structure, not run. So, treat it still works as mostly proven, not gospel. So, how does one short prompt pull this off? A ladder. It\'s the'

[02:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'old YAGNI rule, you aren\'t going to need it, turned into a reflex. Before writing anything, the agent stops at the first rung that holds. Does this need to exist at all? Does the standard library'

[02:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'already do it? A native platform feature? Something already installed? Can it be one line? Only at the very bottom does it write new code. Most tasks never reach the bottom. But, here\'s the part the hype skips. Lazy is'

[03:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not negligent. Watch where it refuses to cut. Ask for a user endpoint, and it deletes the controller, the service, the repository. Five files of ceremony around one database call down to nine'

[03:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lines. But, the response schema? It keeps that. Return the raw database model instead, and you\'d leak every column you never meant to expose. So,'

[03:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cut the layers, keep the trust boundary. Validation, data loss, security, accessibility, those are never on the block. And every shortcut it does take gets a Pony Tail comment naming the ceiling and'

[03:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the fix. Non-trivial logic still leaves one runnable check behind. Corners cut on the record, not in the dark. The cleverest move is distribution. It\'s one rule set, but it ships to 13 different'

[03:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'agents. Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, Copilot, Gemini. Same idea, mirrored into each one\'s config format. The product isn\'t software. The product'

[04:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is a prompt, and that\'s increasingly what a tool on GitHub even is. So, here\'s that catch. The file works because a senior dev wrote the ceilings into it. Strip those out, and you don\'t get senior taste. You just get less'

[04:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'code. That\'s the senior dev compressed into a file. 1744 bytes, MIT, link below. Go read all of it. It\'s shorter than the config file you\'ll skip on the'

[04:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way there. And if you want to know how your agent actually decides any of this, our agent mechanics series is right there.'
